<subSubSection id="B961D0313C72DF83D27C5D0FBC867BF7" pageNumber="350" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="907A644AA1DBEF98CF629544BBD2ADDC" pageNumber="350">
<emphasis id="7CCC27890B1C69CF133F959D70D6ED20" italics="true" pageNumber="350">Note:</emphasis>
Reveal &amp; al. (in 
<emphasis id="55726EE051CDB7DDC39873ABEB1D80C4" italics="true" pageNumber="350">Bartonia</emphasis>
56: 19. 1990) have argued that only part of the Dillenius illustration designated as the 
<typeStatus id="76676C83EA08BDE20A946CE6BA832F11">lectotype</typeStatus>
by Parks was cited under the supposedly 
<normalizedToken id="C5EA6D31470C4E2A66EDA5C9C7E393EC" originalValue="“typical”">&quot;typical&quot;</normalizedToken>
part of 
<normalizedToken id="F22D1D5DAD044E7923AF87F262C1A137" originalValue="Linnaeus’">Linnaeus'</normalizedToken>
protologue, arguing for restriction of the type to a single leaf. However, this seems unhelpful and recent authors such as Strother (in Daniel, 
<emphasis id="8AA69BAD040A0E24145FBA234A0EA73B" italics="true" pageNumber="350">Fl. Chiapas</emphasis>
5: 73. 1999) and Wagner &amp; Robinson (in 
<emphasis id="72FF6514FE3DB6EEB525FF65D84C9FFF" italics="true" pageNumber="350">Brittonia</emphasis>
53: 557. 2002) follow Parks.
</paragraph>
